result.execSummary:
The defendant Jacob T Dziegielewski was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Attempting to Flee or Elude a Traffic Officer, a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 346.04(3).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

supervisions.notes:
In the Wisconsin State Prison System
Consecutive to: any other sentence
Defendant is eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program and the Wisconsin Substance Abuse Program.

If revoked, Court ordered that all court costs, fines, surcharges and/or restitution be paid through collection by the Department of Corrections from 25% of funds under Sec. 973.05(4)(b) and as a condition of extended supervision. DOC shall collect those sums.  Any amount remaining due and owing is subject to civil judgment and/or tax intercept or other means.

miscConds.notes:
CONDITIONS OF PROBATION/EXTENDED SUPERVISION, IF REVOKED:
Follow all rules of supervision and follow through with any other treatment deemed necessary by the department.
AODA assessment and cooperate with any programs deemed necessary by the probation department.

Absolute/maintain sobriety, no alcohol, no drugs. No possession/consumption/selling/distribution of illegal drugs/alcohol. No contact with places where drugs are packaged or sold. Random urine screens.

Provide a DNA sample. Court ordered defendant pay all of the following by the end of supervision: 
All court costs, fees, and surcharges (including DNA); all applicable fees of supervision. Failure to pay will result in a civil judgment.
Court advised defendant that as a convicted felon he may never possess a firearm. Court advised defendant that he may not vote until his civil rights have been restored.
Upon successful completion of the sentence, Court will consider motion for expungement.

The Court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM TERM OF IMPRISONMENT of  3 YEARS 6 MONTHS with 1 day credit CONSECUTIVE to any other sentence; the INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin State Prison System is 1 YEAR 6 MONTHS; the MAXIMUM TERM OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION is 2 YEARS.

Court finds defendant IS eligible for the Challenge Incarceration program and the Earned Release program.  

Court STAYED the sentence and placed the defendant on 2 YEARS probation.  

Conditions of Probation/ Extended Supervision if revoked:
- AODA assessment and cooperate with any programs deemed necessary by the probation department.
- Absolute/maintain sobriety, no alcohol, no drugs.
- No possession/consumption/selling/distribution of illegal drugs/alcohol.
- No contact with places where drugs are packaged or sold.
- Random urine screens.
- Obtain/maintain fulltime employment/education/vocation.
- Provide a DNA sample.
- Follow all rules of supervision and follow through with any other treatment deemed necessary by the department.

Court ordered the defendant pay all of the following by the end of supervision.  Failure to pay will result in a civil judgment:
All court costs, fees, and surcharges (including DNA); 
All applicable fees of supervision.

Defendant Jacob T Dziegielewski in court with attorney Debra J. Patterson.  Michael Lonski appeared for the State of Wisconsin on behalf of Irene Partyhum.
 Defendant changes plea to GUILTY. Defendant examined as to his plea, advised of his Constitutional rights and the maximum penalty. Court found that defendant freely, voluntarily and intelligently waived his rights. Plea questionnaire received and filed. Parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis to sustain defendant's plea. Court found defendant guilty as charged in the information and ordered a Judgment of Conviction be entered on the record. Defendant is advised he is a convicted felon and may not possess any firearms. Defendant is advised he is unable to vote in any election until civil rights are restored. Defendant further advised that if he is not a US citizen deportation is possible.  PSI was NOT ordered. Case set for sentencing in Branch 22.  

  Sentencing hearing scheduled for 09-24-2014 at 01:30 pm.
